FEATURES INDICATE A PATTERN OF MCGN TYPE 1

Steroid Resistant Nephrotic Syndrome

Normally when blood flows through the kidneys, they filter out the waste products and hold onto the rest including protein and most of the water. However, in nephrotic syndrome, the kidneys become leaky and cannot hold onto protein and it too leaks out with the waste. When the protein leaks out this is drops the level of protein in the blood and this is enough to make a child unwell. When the blood level of protein drops, water leaks out into the tissues and can be seen as children get puffy. This is called Nephrotic Syndrome.

The cause of Nephrotic Syndrome in most cases is unknown, although we are learning more about the disease and the changes it can cause in the kidney cells. Also we are learning more about genes which are involved more about this later!

Doctors will try to treat the disease with steroids in the first instance, however when these do not work the Nephrotic Syndrome is defined as being Steroid Resistant Nephrotic Syndrome (SRNS) this can include one type known as focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS).

Steroid resistant nephrotic syndrome (SRNS) can be a difficult disease to control even with other strong medicine and it can sometimes cause significant kidney damage leading to kidney failure.

If a child with SRNS or FSGS has kidney failure and needs a kidney transplant, there is a chance that the illness can come back after the transplant. This is more likely with subsequent transplants than with the first. It can often be treated and can get completely better, but this is also difficult to achieve.

The glomerular filtration barrier

The functional unit of the kidney is known as the nephron. At one end there is the glomerulus which is connected to the tubule. It is the glomerulus that is important in the development of nephrotic syndrome. Blood, is pumped from the heart around the circulation to the kidneys. Inside the kidney, the blood travels in narrow blood vessels. The glomerulus sit very close to these blood vessels. There is transfer of waste products, salts and some water from the blood across into the glomerulus. This is controlled by the barrier (sieve) between the two. We call this the glomerular filtration barrier and it is made up of three layers (the blood vessel wall known as the endothelium, the glomerular basement membrane and a specialised cell known as the podocyte).

The podocyte cell

The podocyte cell is a very specialised cell. It has a central body and many feet which sit over the basement membrane and endothelium in the glomerular filtration barrier. These feet lie very close to feet from other podocyte cells and work together to form a sieve. In nephrotic syndrome the feet dont develop as normal and the holes of the sieve become bigger causing protein to leak out of the blood vessels with the waste products. This results in protein leaking into the urine causing the clinical picture of nephrotic syndrome.

The Study Group

Professor Moin Saleem is the head of the Academic Renal Unit based in North Bristol as well as Consultant in Paediatric Kidney Medicine at the Childrens Hospital in Bristol. He has developed a special interest in the biology of the cells involved in nephrotic syndrome and why these malfunction which results in the kidneys becoming leaky to protein. The laboratory is well known throughout the world for this work.

The analysis of the samples will be undertaken by members of the research team including scientists, a laboratory technician and a doctor who is training to be a consultant in paediatric kidney medicine. They are all based in the laboratory in North Bristol which is secure and requires ID access to get in.

The Research Project

There are three main parts to this study. Firstly each patient has consented to their clinical information being uploaded onto the RaDaR database. This information will be pooled for all patients and, using statistics, will be analysed. We are looking for patterns for instance whether it is more common in boys than girls. Although these patterns have been looked for before, it has not been done in such a big group or in the UK.

Secondly we would like to look at genes associated with SRNS/FSGS. Over the last ten years our knowledge about what goes wrong in the cells of the kidney has increased significantly. Associated with this, we have found that, in some cases, these problems are caused by abnormal coding of our genes.

Genes are inherited from our mother and fathers and sit in each of our cells. They are like a computer program that tells the cell how to work and what to produce to do the job they are designed for. Sometimes, during our development the genes are altered so that they do not work as well and sometimes we can inherit abnormal genes from our mother or father. We refer to these alterations as gene mutations.

In this study we would like to test for the gene mutations that can cause SRNS/FSGS. It is not known how many children will have a gene mutation but other studies suggest that in children without another family member affected, there is a 15-20% chance of having a mutation causing the SRNS/FSGS.

When the genes are tested, the results will be fed back to the patients kidney doctor (if this is what the patient has consented to) and they will discuss the findings. There is also a link to information about the genes being tested below.

Having tested the children for these genes we will compare how the disease differs in those with gene mutations compared with those without, and hopefully learn more about what causes the disease, and how to manage it better.

Lastly, the laboratory in Bristol has developed markers of how active the disease is in blood or plasma samples, in the context of the illness coming back after transplantation. We would like to explore this further on a larger number of samples to validate these findings and try and develop a test to predict the chance of recurrence of the illness after transplantation. These are called biomarkers and look at particular biological-pathways inside the kidney cells and their response to disease. This will be important in being able to advise patients in advance about the risks and benefits of transplantation for each individual.

The genes being tested

Nephrin (NPHS1)

The NPHS1 gene codes to make a protein called Nephrin that is only found in the podocyte cells in the kidney.

Nephrin is important in maintaining the shape of the podocyte cell in the kidneys and controls some of the signalling that occurs inside the podocyte cell. Without it the cells do not maintain normal structure and this affects the glomerular filtration barrier function making the kidney leaky.

It was found in 1998 by a group looking at a condition called the Finnish type of congenital nephrotic syndrome which occurs in babies in the first few months of life.

However, very recently, a handful of children who have developed SRNS after the age of 1year, have been found to have mutations in this gene. They had nephrotic syndrome which was resistant to steroids and other medications but generally had a slow progression of disease.

Podocin (NPHS2)

The NPHS2 gene codes for a protein called Podocin which again is only found in the podocyte cell in the kidney. Podocin works closely with Nephrin in maintaining the structural shape of the slit diaphragm and helps the Nephrin signal to other parts of the cell. Like Nephrin, the absence of Podocin causes dysfunction of the glomerular filtration barrier resulting in protein leak from the kidneys.

It was found in 2000 and has since been shown to be relatively common (in about 25%) of children affected by FSGS where other members of the family are also affected. It also occurs in children where there is no family history but is not as common. It is thought that children with Podocin mutations have a lower risk of the disease coming back after transplantation than children without.

PLCe1 (NPHS3)

This gene was found in 2006 and codes for a protein (phospholipase C epsilon) which helps with sending signals around the podocyte cell. It also helps with development of the podocyte and so in its absence the cells probably do not fully develop and it can again cause disruption to the glomerular filtration barrier which results in protein leak from kidneys.

WT1

This gene codes for Wilms Tumour Suppressor Gene 1 which when mutated can cause several illnesses in children. It can cause a severe form of nephrotic syndrome in infants under one known as diffuse mesangial sclerosis but it can also cause FSGS. Often the nephrotic syndrome is associated with other abnormalities such as eye problems or genitourinary problems.

TRPC6

This is a gene which codes for a protein which sits on the surface of the podocyte cell and controls the entry of calcium into the cell which in turn is important for signalling within the cell.

In 1999 a group studying a large family where the disease affected several members in adulthood, found that this gene was mutated and responsible for them developing FSGS. This has been repeated with other families where several members are affected. More recently it was described in a child for the first time.

CD2AP

This is a gene that codes for a protein located in podocyte cells and other cells. In the podocyte it works with Nephrin and Podocin and helps maintain the structure of the cell. It has been found in children and adults that when it is mutated it can cause loss of the special function of the podocyte cells and the glomerular filtration barrier and therefore the kidneys leak protein.

Alpha-actinin 4

This gene codes for a protein which again is involved with maintaining the structure and therefore function of the podocyte cell interacting with Nephrin and Podocin in the process. It was first identified in 1998 and initial work found that in a large family where several members had FSGS and no other cause was identified, then this gene was found to be mutated. So far almost all work with this has looked at adults with FSGS; this will be the biggest group of children to be tested for it.

Support groups

The UK National Kidney Federation www.kidney.org.uk

The NKF is the national charity in the United Kingdom Run by Kidney Patients for Kidney Patients.

The Federations aim throughout the UK is to promote both the best renal medical practice and treatment, and the health of persons suffering from Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) or Established Renal Failure (ERF).

The NKF also supports the related needs of those relatives and friends who care for kidney patients.

Nephrotic Support Trust www.nstrust.co.uk

The Nephrotic Syndrome Trust, or NeST, was set up in 2005 by trustee David Yearsley whose son James sufferers from the disease, and is now run by Wendy Cook, another parent caring for a child with NS.

Nephrotic Syndrome affects around 10,000 people in the UK. Doctors do not fully understand the cause and there is currently no known cure. But a dedicated team at the specialist Kidney Unit at Bristol Children's hospital is researching the disorder in hope of finding a cure.

This research work is funded solely by charitable donations and grants and has to proceed on a project-by-project basis. It was for this reason that a dedicated charity has been set up to raise money to fund this vital research.

The Trust aims to:

  • Raise awareness of the disease
  • Raise funds for research to find a cure
  • Offer a website resource and forum for sufferers and their carers who often feel isolated

NeST is supported by the world-renowned rugby player Jona Lomu himself a sufferer of NS who has agreed to be an Ambassador for the charity.

Our NSTrust Community Bulletin Board is now up and running and you can read and post messages relating to Nephrotic Syndrome and NeST.

Nephcure International www.nephcure-international.org

Nephrotic Syndrome, a rare disease, affects thousands of individuals throughout the world, hundreds more are diagnosed every day. NephCure International (NI), a newly organized consortium of eight (8) countries, is the only global patient organization solely dedicated to finding a cause and a cure for Idiopathic Nephrotic Syndrome. Comprised and supported by patients, families and researchers from all over the world, NI is empowered by hope and perseverance in pursuit of its mission.

Together these countries, will share their ideas, combine their strengths and support each other in order to grow.

Together we stand for all patients and are dedicated to: Provide information, education, support and advocacy for patients and their families, while raising overall public awareness

Membranoproliferative Glomerulonephritis and Dense deposit Disease

What does the name "membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis" mean?

Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis (MPGN) is the name given to a group of related kidney disorders. Some doctors use the term mesangiocapillary glomerulonephritis instead, but the two names refer to the same group of conditions.

Glomerulonephritis is the technical word to describe inflammation of the special blood vessels in the kidney that filter the bloodstream. The filters are known as glomeruli, hence the name. The diagnosis of MPGN is made by a kidney biopsy, and describes the pattern of inflammation seen in the filters.

MPGN is traditionally divided into three groups; type 1, type 2 and type 3. This division is made according to some of the details seen in the biopsy. In some people there is an overlap of features so that pathologists cannot always clearly allocate a definite sub-type to every MPGN patient. However, MPGN type 2 is sufficiently different from the other types to have its own diagnostic term, Dense Deposit Disease (DDD).

How is the diagnosis made?

Inflammation in the kidney filters, glomerulonephritis, allows blood and protein from the plasma to escape into the urine. Often it is finding blood and protein in the urine that leads to investigation for kidney condition. Urine is mostly water that has been filtered out of the blood plasma by the kidneys. The filters do not normally allow red blood cells or protein (albumin) into the urine. (Albumin in the human blood stream is very like chicken albumin which is the clear gelatinous "white" of an egg.)

Patients may have so great a loss of albumin into the urine that their blood level of albumin is low. This can cause the body to retain fluids leading to swelling (oedema).  This sequence of events is called nephrotic syndrome. MPGN is just one possible cause of nephrotic syndrome.

Some patients with MPGN will have reduced kidney function. That is to say waste products that are normally excreted (removed) in the urine can build up in the body. Usually there are few symptoms from this, and a simple blood test is used to see how well the kidneys are functioning. People with MPGN often have signs of anaemia (they look pale and lack energy), and quite often get high blood pressure.

Blood tests help to exclude alternative diagnoses. However the diagnosis can only be made for certain with a kidney biopsy.

Kidney biopsy.

The small core of kidney tissue obtained by a biopsy is cut into thin slices, stained, and looked at under a microscope. Special stains are used to identify key components of the immune system (such as complement components discussed below). Usually the biopsy is also examined with an electron microscope. This essential to diagnose DDD, the characteristic dense deposits that give the condition it name are seen in the filter membranes of the kidney.

What causes MPGN?  

For most people with MPGN the cause of the problem is not fully known. However, certain infections can cause it, for example hepatitis C infection.  In some patients there are defects in the way their immune system is regulated. Understanding how the immune system causes disease has improved recently, although more need to be done. It raises hope for better treatment in future. Some problems of regulating the immune system are genetic. Others are acquired. Some of the infective or immune problems seem to relate to the specific types of MPGN or DDD.

A part of the immune system that is important in MPGN is known as the Complement System.  The Complement System is used to kill germs very quickly and defend us from infection. It is made up of several proteins that are naturally present in body fluids. When they are activated, they send signals to the body's white blood cells, and they join together to create small holes (pores) in membranes. When this happens on the surface of a bacterium, for example, it quickly kills it.  Complement would be dangerous if it was activated against our own healthy tissues by mistake. There is a system of regulators to make sure that it does not.

In MPGN, complement is seen in the kidney filters. It should not be there. It is almost certainly capable of causing the kind of damage that one gets in MPGN. 

There are different ways of activating complement. One uses immunoglobulins (antibodies), another group of proteins that recognise germs and direct the complement system to work right where it is needed on an invading bacterium or virus. In MPGN type 1 and type 3 we typically find immunoglobulin and complement together, meaning that this pathway is being used. For example, antibodies known as cryoglobulins, probably caused indirectly by infection, can activate complement and get deposited in kidney filters. Cryoglobulins are associated with MPGN and can be detected in a blood test.

Another pathway does not use immunoglobulin. Complement gets activated by itself. This suggests that some of the normal regulators of complement are not working properly. This pattern is more usual in MPGN type 2 (DDD). For example, some patients have a deficiency of Factor H, an important regulator of complement. This defect allows complement to be activated in the wrong place at the wrong time, such as in the kidney. Animals bred to have a genetic fault in Factor H get MPGN, confirming the importance of this idea.

To make matters more complex, some people with MPGN of various types develop antibodies against complement itself. These are known as nephritic factors. They cause complement to be activated and escape the normal regulatory processes. One can test for the presence of nephritic factor in blood. It is not known why some people make it.

What happens to people with MPGN?

For most patients, MPGN is slowly progressive. Without treatment kidneys tend to wear out over a decade because of the inflammation and damage to the filters (glomeruli). All our glomeruli are made before we are born. After that if some are damaged and lost they can not be replaced. Kidneys have evolved to have considerable spare capacity, so kidney function can hold up in spite of quite a lot of damage. The amount of damage can be assessed from a kidney biopsy. The level of kidney function is assessed on a blood test that measures a waste product such as creatinine. If the creatinine level goes up it is because the kidney function has gone down.  If kidney function becomes very low, below about a tenth of normal, patients will need dialysis or a kidney transplant.

Sometimes the disease goes into remission, either because of treatment or spontaneously. Remission is indicated when the blood and protein in the urine go away and the urine tests return to normal. If this happens it implies that the inflammation in the kidney has ceased. Sometime the blood tests show that the immune system remains abnormal even though the kidney problem has improved.

In a few patients the disease is especially aggressive and kidney function declines rapidly. For an individual patient it is not possible to predict exactly how quickly or slowly the disease will go. However it there is a lot of damage already present at the beginning of the illness this is unfavourable. The kidney biopsy is useful in telling how much damage has already occurred.

Treatment options

As the immune system is involved in the disease process, immune suppressing treatments have been used. Some, such as corticosteroids (Prednisolone), have shown benefit in trials, but they are not always well tolerated and side effects are common. There is a lack of good quality trial information on the newer immunosuppressant medicines. This is because different types of MPGN and DDD might respond differently to different classes of drug. Many of the older studies have not distinguished between the various sub-types of MPGN, so they are difficult to interpret. Better, modern studies are needed.

There is a lot that can be done to improve wellbeing even if it does not address the root cause of the problem. These days many patients will be treated with angiotensin antagonists/inhibitors to reduce the wastage of protein in the urine and improve blood pressure. Diuretic medicines (medicines that help get rid of water from the body) can help control oedema (swelling). Nutritional support helps to keep up the strength of bones and muscles. Attention to detail is important, and decisions have to be tailored to each person's needs. Patients with MPGN or DDD should be closely supervised by a renal physician or a paediatric nephrologist.

If the kidney damage becomes severe enough, and kidney function is too low, kidney replacement treatment becomes necessary. This might involve dialysis or kidney transplantation. Some patients get MPGN in the transplanted kidney. This is not necessarily as severe as the original illness, and some people show evidence of the process in a transplant kidney biopsy with very little in the way of disease activity. However, some will lose the transplant because of disease recurrence. There needs to be a careful evaluation of a patient's transplant risks early on, although predicting the risk is not well refined.

MPGN studies

The MPGN Working Group is a consortium of doctors, scientists and others who study different aspects of MPGN and provide better information for patients and professionals. The Group is collecting clinical and laboratory information on as many children and adults with MPGN and DDD as possible. It is also looking to perform new treatment trials. For information about the group click the MPGN/DDD Working Group link here.
